⭐ Q2. Explain the core characteristics of Big Data (Volume, Velocity, Variety, Veracity) with real-world examples. [IMP]

The core characteristics of Big Data are traditionally defined by the "4 Vs":

Volume (Scale of Data):
Explanation: Refers to the unimaginably massive amount of data generated every second. We are no longer talking about Gigabytes, but Terabytes, Petabytes, and Exabytes.
Real-World Example: Facebook stores over 300 Petabytes of user data, and hundreds of hours of video are uploaded to YouTube every single minute.
Velocity (Speed of Data):
Explanation: Refers to the unprecedented speed at which new data is being generated, processed, and analyzed. Big data often requires real-time or near-real-time processing.
Real-World Example: Millions of stock market trades happening in milliseconds, or credit card companies analyzing swipe data instantly to detect and block fraudulent transactions before the receipt prints.
Variety (Diversity of Data):
Explanation: Refers to the different forms and formats of data. Data no longer comes just in neat rows and columns (structured); it comes in highly diverse formats (unstructured and semi-structured).
Real-World Example: A smart city network collects structured data from traffic sensors, semi-structured JSON data from weather APIs, and unstructured video data from CCTV cameras simultaneously.
Veracity (Uncertainty of Data):
Explanation: Refers to the quality, trustworthiness, and accuracy of the data. When dealing with massive volumes, data is often messy, incomplete, or contains "noise."
Real-World Example: Twitter data is heavily used for sentiment analysis, but tweets often contain typos, slang, fake news, or bot-generated spam, making the data highly uncertain.
