Big Data Processing Architecture Design: A standard Big Data architecture handles the massive flow of data from its raw creation all the way to final business analysis. It is divided into distinct logical layers:

Data Sources Layer: The origin of the data. Includes relational databases, enterprise applications, IoT sensors, social media feeds, and server logs.
Data Ingestion / Collection Layer: Responsible for acquiring data from the sources. Uses tools like Apache Kafka (for real-time streaming data) or Apache Sqoop (for batch loading SQL data).
Data Storage Layer: Since the data is massive, it requires distributed storage systems. Data is securely dumped into systems like Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), Cloud Data Lakes (AWS S3), or NoSQL databases (HBase).
Data Processing Layer: The core engine that cleans, transforms, and analyzes the raw data.
• Batch Processing: Handled by Hadoop MapReduce or Apache Spark for massive historical datasets.
• Real-Time Processing: Handled by Apache Storm or Spark Streaming for immediate insights.
Data Consumption / Visualization Layer: The final output layer where processed data is sent to Business Intelligence (BI) tools (like Tableau or PowerBI) to create dashboards, reports, and predictive models for business users.



