⭐ Q2. Explain the architecture and functioning of HDFS (Hadoop Distributed File System) for data storage. [IMP]

➡️ DIAGRAM REQUIRED

HDFS Architecture: HDFS operates on a highly reliable Master/Slave architecture designed specifically to store massive files across commodity hardware.

Core Components & Functioning:
NameNode (The Master):
Function: It is the central controller of the HDFS cluster. It does not store the actual data.

Instead, it maintains the Metadata (the filesystem namespace, directory tree, file permissions, and exactly which DataNodes contain which blocks of a specific file).

It tracks the "health" of the cluster by constantly receiving "Heartbeat" signals from the slaves.

DataNodes (The Slaves):
Function: These are the actual worker machines (hundreds or thousands of them). They physically store the actual raw data.

Blocks: In HDFS, massive files (e.g., a 1GB log file) are split into smaller, fixed-size chunks called Blocks (default size is 128 MB). These blocks are distributed across multiple DataNodes.

Replication (Fault Tolerance):
To guarantee data is never lost if a physical hard drive crashes, HDFS automatically creates copies of every single block.

The default Replication Factor is 3. (e.g., Block 1 of a file is stored on DataNode A, copied to DataNode B, and copied again to DataNode C).

Secondary NameNode:
It is not a backup NameNode. It acts as an assistant that periodically merges namespace image files to prevent the main NameNode's RAM from overflowing.
Q3. Describe the MapReduce Programming Model.

Concept: MapReduce is a core distributed programming model (originally developed by Google) used to write applications that process massive amounts of data in parallel across a massive cluster of thousands of computers.

The Master/Slave Architecture:

• JobTracker (Master):
Receives the job from the client, divides it into smaller tasks, and schedules them on the worker nodes.

• TaskTracker (Slave):
Runs on every worker node and executes the actual data processing tasks assigned by the JobTracker.

The Two Fundamental Phases:
The Map Phase:
The raw input data is split into independent chunks.

The "Mapper" function processes these chunks in parallel on different nodes. It filters, sorts, or parses the data.

Output: It generates a massive list of intermediate Key-Value pairs.

The Reduce Phase:
The intermediate Key-Value pairs generated by the Mappers are shuffled, sorted, and grouped strictly by their "Keys".

The "Reducer" function receives these grouped keys and aggregates, sums, or summarizes the values.

Output: The final, condensed result is written back to HDFS.

⭐ Q4. Explain the MapReduce processing steps in detail, including Map Tasks, Combiners, Partitioning, and Reduce Tasks. [IMP]

A complete MapReduce job executes in several strict, sequential steps to process Big Data efficiently.

Input Splits & Record Reader:
The massive input file in HDFS is logically divided into Input Splits (usually matching the 128MB block size). The Record Reader converts this raw data into basic Key-Value pairs and feeds them to the Mapper.
Map Task:
The user-defined Map function executes the core business logic (like filtering or tokenizing). It processes the input and generates millions of intermediate Key-Value pairs.
Combiner (Optional but Highly Recommended):
A Combiner is essentially a "Mini-Reducer" that runs locally on the exact same node as the Mapper immediately after the Map phase.

Function: It performs a local aggregation before sending the data over the network.

Partitioner:
The Partitioner decides exactly which Reducer will receive which Key-Value pairs.

It usually uses a hash function to guarantee that all values associated with the same Key are sent to the same Reduce Task.

Shuffle and Sort:
The framework transfers the partitioned data across the network to the assigned Reducers. The data is then automatically grouped and sorted by the Key.
Reduce Task:
The user-defined Reduce function receives a Key and a list of all associated values. It aggregates them and writes the final result to HDFS.
⭐ Q5. Describe the functioning of YARN (Hadoop 2 Execution Model) with its architecture diagram. [IMP]

➡️ DIAGRAM REQUIRED

